query: what is a starboard
passage: What is the meaning of port, starboard, bow and stern? The right side of the boat is called the starboard side because it was the side the 'steering board', which we now call an oar or rudder was mounted. Starboard is the old seaman's bastardization of steering board. Since the steering board was mounted on the right side of the boat, that side could not be tied up to the warf or dock when in port. Therefore, the left side of the boat is called the port side because it was the side that was tied up to the warf or dock when in port.

What is the meaning of port, starboard, bow and stern? The right side of the boat is called the starboard side because it was the side the 'steering board', which we now call an oar or rudder was mounted. Starboard is the old seaman's bastardization of steering board. Since the steering board was mounted on the right side of the boat, that side could not be tied up to the warf or dock when in port. Therefore, the left side of the boat is called the port side because it was the side that was tied up to the warf or dock when in port.

The lyric is a basic plea for sex -- Rock me all night long -- while the music provides a blues structure that allows King room for biting guitar work.
